The '''Doctrine of Exchange''' is a central tenet<ref name="Hernandez">[http://caselaw.lp.findlaw.com/scripts/getcase.pl?navby=search&court=US&case=/us/490/680.html ''Hernandez v. Commissioner'', U.S. Supreme Court]</ref> of [[Scientology]], which dictates that for spiritual well-being, "anytime a person receives something, he must pay something back"<ref>http://www.usdoj.gov/osg/briefs/1988/sg880419.txt</ref> and balance "inflow" with "outflow".<ref name="Hernandez" />  The [[Church of Scientology]] has presented this as the reason some of its services, such as [[auditing (Scientology)|auditing]], its central practice of Scientology,<ref>[http://www.e-meter.org.uk/ Scientology Counselling - The Practice of Scientology<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> must never be given away, but must be paid for.

[[Quid pro quo]] transactions are prohibited in tax-exempt organizations,{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}} and the Church of Scientology has argued in its requests for [[tax exemption]] that Scientology courses must have fixed fees because of this religious doctrine.{{Citation needed|date=September 2013}}

==Exceptions==
Not all services fall under the Doctrine.  The Church has identified some services as examples of services where "no donation is expected from members":<ref name="Scientology Today">{{cite web | url=http://www.scientologytoday.org/Common/question/pg35.htm  | title=Scientology Today : ''How are Churches of Scientology supported financially?'' | publisher=Church of Scientology | accessdate=2006-09-22}}</ref>
* Listening to lectures, whether from fellow parishioners or playing [[L. Ron Hubbard]]’s lectures on tape
* Reading Scientology [[scripture]] in the Church library
* Meeting with fellow [[parishioner]]s
* Receiving counseling (but not auditing) from a Scientology [[chaplain]]
* Attending Sunday services, [[sermons]], [[weddings]], [[infant baptism|christening]]s or [[funeral]]s

