The '''Truce of Chinon''', which ended the [[Anglo-French War (1213–1214)|Anglo-French war of 1213–14]], was agreed to by King [[John, King of England|John of England]] and King [[Philip II of France]] on 28 September 1214 at the [[Château de Chinon|castle of Chinon]]. John's attempt to defeat Philip II in 1214, failed due to the French victory over John's allies at the [[battle of Bouvines]]. A peace agreement was signed in which John forfeited the Counties of [[County of Anjou|Anjou]] and [[County of Poitou|Poitou]] and the [[Duchy of Brittany]] and pay £60,000 pounds in reparations to the French crown. The truce was intended to last until Easter 1220.
==References== *William Kibler. ''Medieval France: An Encyclopedia'' Series: Routledge Encyclopedias of the Middle Ages. Routledge, 1995. {{ISBN|978-0824044442}}
