An '''unenforced law''' (also '''symbolic law''') is a crime which is illegal, but is usually not penalized by a jurisdiction. It is a law which is usually ignored by law enforcement, therefore such laws have no consequences.<ref>Modern criminal law; Wayne R. LaFave; P 53</ref> Some people have criticized such laws claiming that it indicates sometimes the law means what it says, sometimes it doesn't.<ref>[http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/2006/02/symboliclaws/ Teenage kissing: The new sex crime?] BBC retrieved 29 January 2012</ref>
==Overview== The law may be put in place simply for symbolic reasons, but without actual prosecutions taking place.<ref name=thells>[https://books.google.com/books?id=DKJ654VkMb8C&pg=PA95&dq=&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7RslT_iJLoXO8QOpr_ziBw&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAg#v=onepage&q=&f=false The legal system: a social science perspective] retrieved 29 January 2012</ref> For example [[Speed limit enforcement|speeding is illegal]], but patrol officers usually ignore motorists who are 5-10 miles an hour over the legal limit.<ref name="lwl">[https://books.google.com/books?id=QSBj8LgEi-kC&pg=PA141&dq=&hl=en&sa=X&ei=WCElT8r1KIrw8QPa_fm9Bw&ved=0CEQQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=&f=false Law Without Values: The Life, Work, and Legacy of Justice Holmes] retrieved 29 January 2012</ref> [[Traffic enforcement camera|Automate ticketing systems like computerized cameras]] will still issue fines in these circumstances in some but not all US states.<ref>http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post/15750/what-is-the-right-level-for-speed-camera-fines/</ref>
Although [[incest]] is illegal in many European countries, it is generally not enforced if between two consenting adults.<ref name="focus-2011-05-22">{{cite web |url=http://www.focus.de/panorama/welt/tid-22414/europaeischer-gerichtshof-geschwisterpaar-bringt-inzest-verbot-ins-wanken_aid_629510.html | title=Geschwisterpaar bringt Inzest-Verbot ins Wanken | date=22 May 2011 | language=German}}</ref>
Laws that are symbolic typically attempt to persuade rather than enforce, punish or prevent.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=cEUkYHBa0CQC&printsec=frontcover&dq=&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7TwlT6LgI8bA8QOr0q29Bw&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=&f=false Law as symbolic form] Deniz Coskun</ref><ref>[http://www.prospectmagazine.co.uk/2006/02/symboliclaws/ Prospective magazine] retrieved 29 January 2012</ref> An example was [[adultery]] in the US state of [[Colorado]], where it was prohibited by law (since repealed), but was not punishable in any way.<ref name="lwl"/> In [[Maryland]] adultery is prohibited by law with just a $10 fine, but not punishable by [[imprisonment]].<ref>[http://mgaleg.maryland.gov/webmga/frmStatutesText.aspx?article=gcr&section=10-501&ext=html&session=2017RS&tab=subject5]</ref>
